===Etymology===
First attested in 1528. From {{etyl|xno|en}} {{term|abeiance||legal expectation|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|abeance||desire|lang=fro}} from {{term|abeer|abeër|to gape at, aspire after|lang=fro}}, {{term|abaer|lang=fro}}, {{term|abair||to desire|lang=fro}}, from {{term|a||to|lang=fro}} + {{term|baer|baër|gape|lang=fro}},<ref>{{R:American Heritage 1971|page=3}}</ref> {{term|bair||yawn|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{term|batō||to yawn|lang=la}}<ref>{{R:MW3 1976|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref>.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/əˈbeɪ.ənts/|/əˈbeɪ.əns/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|Abeyance1 US.ogg|Audio (U.S.A.)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|legal|lang=en}} [[expectancy|Expectancy]]; condition of ownership of real property being [[undetermined]]; lapse in succession of ownership of estate, or title. {{defdate|Late 16<sup>th</sup> century}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=4}}</ref>
#: ''The proceeds of the estate shall be held in '''abeyance''' in an escrow account until the minor reaches age twenty-one.''
#*: ''When there is no person in existence in whom an inheritance (or a dignity) can vest, it is said to be in '''abeyance'''.'' -Blackstone
# [[suspension|Suspension]]; temporary [[suppression]]; dormant condition. {{defdate|Mid 17<sup>th</sup> century}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''2003''', {{w|Bill Bryson}}, ''A Short History of Nearly Everything'', BCA 2003, page 376:
#*: Without a plausible explanation for what might have provoked an ice age, the whole theory fell into '''abeyance'''.
# {{context|heraldry|lang=en}} [[expectancy|Expectancy]] of a title, its right in existence but its exercise suspended.
#: ''The broad pennant of a commodore first class has been in '''abeyance''' since 1958, together with the rank.''

